</span></a><a href = "#H_71A34F76"><span>References</span></a></div></div><h2  class = 'S4' id = 'H_29F3A833' ><span>Introduction</span></h2><div  class = 'S5'><span>This section illustrates an example of calculation of climate financial risk, focusing on energy infrastructure loans, extracted from </span><a href = "#M_F58CDA55"><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>Monasterolo et al. 2018</span></a><span>. The work demonstrates how one can calculate climate policy shocks based on forward-looking trajectories of market shares of energy sectors, by type of technology in fossil fuels and renewable energy, derived by Integrated Assessment Models (IAMs). It then shows how to assess the order of magnitude of changes in value of each bank’s loan, conditional upon a climate policy shock. The analysis is applied to Chinese development banks’ energy infrastructure loans.</span></div><div  class = 'S5'><span>This work is part of a broader stream of research on climate mitigation scenarios and financial risk, discussed in the 2021 Science article by </span><a href = "#M_3DDFF708"><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>Battiston et al. 2021</span></a><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>.</span><span>In particular, it can be applied to the climate scenarios of orderly and disorderly transition developed by the Network for Greening the Financial System (</span><a href = "#M_74321760"><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>NGFS 2020</span></a><span>).</span></div><div  class = 'S5'><span>The approach of connecting IAM scenarios to financial shocks was first introduced in </span><a href = "#M_835CB8B9"><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>Battiston et al. 2017</span></a><span> which developed the general framework to compute: (i) shocks on the value of financial assets (equity holdings, bonds and loans), (ii) financial risk metrics, such as the Climate Value at Risk, and (iii) direct and indirect losses for portfolios of individual financial institutions. This approach can be used for Climate Stress test exercises where indirect losses are computed based on financial network models. This framework has been applied to supervisory data, covering bank loans and investment funds’ holdings in </span><a href = "#M_61EF456C"><span style=' font-weight: bold;'>Roncoroni et al. 2021 </span></a><span>in collaboration with the Central Bank of Mexico.</span></div><h2  class = 'S4' id = 'H_BD8E070F' ><span>Methodology</span></h2><div  class = 'S5'><span>The methodology of Monasterolo et al. 2018, considers a financial actor, </span><span style=' font-style: italic;'>i</span><span>, with a portfolio of investments through contract loans to distinct borrowers, with a valuation model including three time steps: the time at which the valuation is carried out (</span><span texencoding="t_0" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="12" height="19.5" /></span><span>), the time at which a climate policy shock occurs (</span><span texencoding="t^*" style="vertical-align:-5px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="13" height="18.5" /></span><span>), and the maturity of the loan to borrower </span><span style=' font-style: italic;'>j </span><span>(</span><span texencoding="T_j" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="16.5" height="19.5" /></span><span>). Within this scenario, the authors define the following variables:</span></div><ul  class = 'S6'><li  class = 'S7'><span texencoding="A_{ij}" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="18" height="19.5" /></span><span> : the financial valuation at time </span><span texencoding="t_0" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="12" height="19.5" /></span><span> of the investment of bank </span><span style=' font-style: italic;'>i</span><span> in the project </span><span style=' font-style: italic;'>j</span><span>, with maturity </span><span texencoding="T_j" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="16.5" height="19.5" /></span></li><li  class = 'S7'><span texencoding="F_{ij}" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="18" height="19.5" /></span><span> : the face value of the loan</span></li><li  class = 'S7'><span texencoding="p_j" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="15.5" height="19.5" /></span><span>  : the probability at time </span><span texencoding="t_0" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="12" height="19.5" /></span><span> that the borrower, </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">j</span><span>, defaults on the loan at the maturity </span><span texencoding="T_j" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="16.5" height="19.5" /></span></li></ul><div  class = 'S5'><span>The concept of a climate policy shock is then introduced as an occurrence at time  where the economy switches (e.g. driven by a change in agents’ expectations) from a business-as-usual scenario (B), characterized by no climate policy, to scenario P. In P, a climate policy is introduced aimed to reach a specific GHG emission target by 2100, and, as a result, market shares of some economic sectors are affected. It is assumed that this adjustment of the economy (and the expectations) modifies the probability of default of the borrower  through changes in the market share of the economic sector of  </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">j</span><span> through changes in the market share of the economic sector of </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">j</span><span>. Hence, a change in default probability implies a proportional change in the expected value of the loan as:</span></div><div  class = 'S8'><span texencoding="\Delta A_{i,j}\left(t_0,T_j,P\right)=-F_{i,j}(1-r_j)\Delta p_j(P)" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="228.5" height="19.5" /></span></div><div  class = 'S5'><span>With the aim on defining this change in default probability, the authors assume that a relative change in the market share of borrower </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">j</span><span>’s sector </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">S</span><span> within the geographic region </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">R</span><span>, denoted by </span><span texencoding="u_{S,R}\left(P, M, t^*\right)" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="83" height="20.5" /></span><span>, implies a proportional relative change in </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">j</span><span>’s profitability. Hence, by defining a market share shock as:</span></div><div  class = 'S8'><span texencoding="u_{S,R}\left(P,M,t^*\right)= \frac{m_{S,R}\left(P,M,t^*\right) - m_{S,R}\left(B,M,t^*\right) }{m_{S,R}\left(B,M,t^*\right) }" style="vertical-align:-18px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="286" height="41" /></span></div><div  class = 'S5'><span>Under the assumption described in the article, the authors prove that the change in expected value of a loan, conditional to a change from scenario B to scenario P, reads as:</span></div><div  class = 'S8'><span texencoding="\Delta A_{i,j}=F_{i,j}(1-r_j)\frac{E_j}{\delta}\chi u_{S,R}\left(P,M,t^*\right)" style="vertical-align:-15px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="226.5" height="37" /></span></div><div  class = 'S5'><span>where</span></div><ul  class = 'S6'><li  class = 'S7'><span texencoding="E_j" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="17" height="19.5" /></span><span> : the initial equity level of the borrower</span></li><li  class = 'S7'><span texencoding="r_j" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="14" height="19.5" /></span><span>  : the recovery rate for borrower </span><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">j</span></li><li  class = 'S7'><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">χ</span><span>  : the elasticity coefficient between profitability and market share</span></li><li  class = 'S7'><span style="font-family: STIXGeneral, STIXGeneral-webfont, serif; font-style: italic; font-weight: 400; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">δ</span><span>  : width of the distribution of the idiosyncratic shocks</span></li></ul><div  class = 'S5'><span>For the sake of simplicity, it is further assumed that:</span></div><ul  class = 'S6'><li  class = 'S7'><span texencoding="E_j / \delta = 1" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="58.5" height="19.5" /></span><span>  Corresponding to the assumption that the magnitude of the initial net worth and width of the distribution of the idiosyncratic shocks are comparable. </span></li><li  class = 'S7'><span texencoding="r_j = 0" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="40" height="19.5" /></span><span>       This case corresponds to the upper bound of the loss incurred on a given loan. </span></li><li  class = 'S7'><span texencoding="\chi = 1" style="vertical-align:-5px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="38" height="17.5" /></span><span>       This is a special case</span></li></ul><div  class = 'S5'><span>These parameters should be calibrated based on the specific application. Hence, the change in expected value of a loan reads as:</span></div><div  class = 'S8'><span texencoding="\Delta A_{i,j}=F_{i,j}u_{S,R}\left(P,M,t^*\right)" style="vertical-align:-6px"><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="151.5" height="20.5" /></span></div><h2  class = 'S4' id = 'H_B02E875C' ><span>Data</span></h2><div  class = 'S5'><span>In order to calculate the market share shocks, one can use any of the available IAM models. As an example, using the NGFS database one can query the total net production of electricity in the World and the corresponding subsector corresponding to Coal.</span></div><div class = 'preformatted-matlab' style = 'margin: 10px 3px 10px 55px; padding: 10px 10px 10px 5px; '><div  class = 'S9'><span style="white-space: pre"><span >c = iam.data.IIASAconnection(</span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">'ngfs'</span><span >);</span></span></div><div  class = 'S9'><span style="white-space: pre"><span >e = iam.IAMEnvironment(c);</span></span></div><div  class = 'S9'><span style="white-space: pre"><span >ts = e.getTimeSeries(</span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">'model'</span><span >,</span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">"GCAM5.3_NGFS"</span><span >,</span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">'regions'</span><span >,</span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">"World"</span><span >, </span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">'Variables'</span><span >, </span><span style="color: rgb(14, 0, 255);">...</span></span></div><div  class = 'S9'><span style="white-space: pre"><span >                     [</span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">"Secondary Energy|Electricity"</span><span >, </span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">"Secondary Energy|Electricity|Coal"</span><span >], </span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">'strict'</span><span >, true)</span></span></div></div><div  class = 'S5'><span></span></div><div  class = 'S5'><span>Similarly, the climate data for the article of this example was obtained using </span><a href = "https://tntcat.iiasa.ac.at/LIMITSDB/dsd?Action=htmlpage&amp;page=about"><span>LIMITS database</span></a><span> and then stored into a .MAT file for ease of use. The full database can be downloaded as a CSV file directly from </span><a href = "https://tntcat.iiasa.ac.at/LIMITSPUBLICDB/dsd?Action=htmlpage&amp;page=register1-3"><span>the database main website</span></a><span>. The authors collected data from two models, (GCAM and WITCH) and three different scenarios (Base, RefPol500, StrPol450). In turn, each of this model-scenario pairs, contains data on 10 relevant regions and several variables.</span></div><div class="CodeBlock"><div class="inlineWrapper"><div  class = 'S10'><span </span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">"PAC_OECD"</span><span >, </span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4, 249);">"REF_ECON"</span><span >, </span><span style="color: rgb(170, 4,
